Arrays Assignment
4/28/26

An array in programing is a set of objects or variables. In C++, declaring an array looks like:

(datatype) myArray[(array length)];

where datatype could be any datatype, and the length would be how many entries the array has.
When accessing an array, it looks like:

myArray[(index of element)];

Within arrays, the index actually starts at zero. Say we declare an array of 5 integers: {1, 2, 3, 4, 5},
1 would be at index 0, 2 would be at index 1, 3 would be at index 2, so on and so forth.
A special kind of array is the multidimensional or 2d array, which is like arrays within an array. They can be visualized as a table of elements. We declare them like:

(datatype) my2DArray[(rows of table)][(columns of table)];

Say we create:

int ints [2][2] = {1 , 2}, {3, 4};

1 would be at ints[0][0];
2 would be at ints[0][1];
3 would be at ints[1][0];
4 would be at ints[1][1];
